      "SummaryText": "Ormat Nevada, Inc. operates the Ormesa Geothermal Projects near the cities of Holtville and El Centro in Imperial County, California within the East Mesa Known Geothermal Resource Area. In 2003, after all ownership merged into one owner entity called  ?Ormesa, LLC?, Ormat Nevada began operation of the Ormesa Geothermal Projects to generate electricity from renewable geothermal resources.  The Ormesa Geothermal Projects were formerly known as the \"East Mesa Geothermal Projects\" and are designated as EPA Facility ID Number 1000 0016 5251.\n\nThe Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) code of the Ormesa facility is 4911 and the equivalent North America Industrial Classification System (NAICS) code is 221119.  Ormat Nevada, Inc. operates the Ormesa Geothermal Project in accordance with all applicable federal, state, and local environmental and safety regulations and is committed to maintaining compliance with these regulations.  Ormesa has emergency response procedures and protocol in place at the facility in coordination with local emergency response agencies.  \n\nThe facility consists of six independent geothermal power plants known as the Ormesa Geothermal Projects, and are comprised of  four Binary Geothermal Power Plants designated as Ormesa Geothermal I (OGI), Ormesa Geothermal IE (OGIE), Ormesa Geothermal II (OGII), Ormesa Geothermal IH (OGIH) and a Dual Flash Geothermal Power plant designated as GEM 2&3 (GEM 2&3 are operated as one combined power plant).  The OGI, OGIE, OGII, and OGIH power plants use isopentane, which is listed by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) and Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) as flammable material, and chlorine, an OSHA- and EPA-designated toxic substance, in quantities that exceed the threshold limits of the Process Safety Management (PSM) program and Risk Management Plan (RMP).  As such these facilities are subject to these applicable regulations and requirements.  Since Ormesa Geothermal IE and IH are in re"
    },
