      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 41953,
      "SummaryText": "mote locations that are not regularly or normally manned, these facilities are essentially exempt from the PSM regulations.  Because the processes at these units are functionally identical, however, this combined plan in applicable to all four facilities. \n\nEach of the four physically separate facilities is covered by the PSM and RMP regulations, which requires proactive identification, evaluation and mitigation or prevention of chemical releases that could occur as a result of failures in processes procedures, or equipment.  The PSM/RMP regulations also define the responsibilities of employers and contractors involved in work that affects or takes place near processes covered by the regulations to ensure the safety of both plant and contractor employees and the potential effects on public receptors (RMP only).\n\nThe primary chemicals used at each facility that are covered by PSM/RMP regulations are isopentane and chlorine gas.  In the binary process of electrical generation, Isopentane is used as the motive fluid in the generation of electricity from natural geothermal fluid in a series of interconnected Ormat Energy Converters (OECs) at each facility.  Geothermal fluid is used to heat isopentane liquid to vapor in the OEC, which in turn is used as the motive fluid to spin a turbine connected to a generator to produce electricity.  The isopentane vapor is then condensed and reused in a continuous, closed loop process within each OEC that does not involve any chemical reactions or changes to the isopentane. At each facility, isopentane is also stored in one or more storage tanks.\n\nChlorine is used in the water treatment system to inhibit bacterial growth in the cooling towers.  The water from the cooling towers is used to condense the isopentane vapor into a liquid during the generation of electricity.  Makeup water for the cooling tower is obtained from a nearby irrigation canal.  At each facility, chlorine gas is stored in one or more 1-ton cylinders.  \nThe GEM 2 &"
