      "SummaryText": " 3 power plant is a dual flash process and does not utilize Isopentane or Chlorine. The geothermal steam turns the turbines a turbine connected to a generator to produce electricity. \n\nThe Ormesa Geothermal Projects are physically located in a relatively remote area, with no nearby residences and publicly accessible properties.  The nearest publicly used or accessible area is the Desert Hot Springs recreation area at the southern boundary of the facility, approximately three miles from the nearest isopentane and chlorine storage tanks. \n\nAn integral element of the PSM/RMP is the process hazard analysis of the storage and use of isopentane and chlorine gas.  In 1994 and 1997, a process hazard analysis was performed using the Hazards and Operability (HAZOP) study in accordance with the guidelines of OSHA and the American Institute of Chemical Engineers.  The previous HAZOP analysis for isopentane concluded that potential deviations could be categorized as ?acceptable with appropriate controls? or ?acceptable as is? and identified appropriate response procedures to use in the remote likelihood of occurrence.  A supplemental ?What If? analysis was also performed at that time.\n\nAs part of the 5-year review, the previous HAZOP analysis was updated, including the ?what-if? checklists, where appropriate.  The HAZOP and ?What-If? analyses were also updated to include the chlorine gas stored and used at the facilities. The HAZOP analysis for chlorine gas concluded that potential deviations can also be categorized as ?acceptable with appropriate controls? or ?acceptable as is? and identified appropriate response procedures to be used in the remote likelihood of their occurrence.\nAn off-site consequence analysis was recently completed to address the additional requirements of the RMP regulations that were not included in the previous PSM rule.  The off-site consequence analysis for the RMP addresses a worst-case release event based on the highly improbable release of the entire"
